WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.680
 Hello, and welcome to my lecture where I share my thoughts on the use of artificial intelligence

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:08.060
 in programming classes.

00:00:08.060 --> 00:00:12.160
 My name is Charles Severance, and I'm a professor at the University of Michigan School of Information

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:14.200
 in Ann Arbor, Michigan.

00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:18.320
 So you may know me from some of my online classes, Python for Everybody, Three Million

00:00:18.320 --> 00:00:22.320
 Students, the largest programming class in the world, Django for Everybody, C Programming

00:00:22.320 --> 00:00:23.320
 for Everybody.

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:30.640
 And I'm building a series of curriculums, a series of courses that lead towards what

00:00:30.640 --> 00:00:35.280
 I call a master programmer, which is a way to get people to become very skilled programmers

00:00:35.280 --> 00:00:42.640
 in shorter time by giving the essential foundations of programming rather than a four-year degree.

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:44.720
 So it's much less than a four-year degree.

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:50.160
 That's my goal right now is to make programmers faster and better.

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:53.480
 So the goals of this presentation are not to make policy for my course or any other

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:55.000
 course.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.440
 Policies really depend on the course and the goals of the course and the course material

00:00:58.440 --> 00:00:59.640
 and the instructor.

00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:05.160
 So don't use this as like telling your teacher that somehow they should change their policies

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:07.120
 because of Dr. Chuck's talk.

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:11.720
 These are just my experiences and opinions and ways I've learned things over time and

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:17.580
 my theories and how I try to explain to my students about the good and the bad about

00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:22.640
 using AI when working in a programming, taking a programming class.

00:01:22.640 --> 00:01:27.040
 So to AI or not to AI, that is the question.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:30.800
 Well, I think the answer is you have to use it.

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:34.560
 From now on, AI is part of software development.

00:01:34.560 --> 00:01:36.160
 You can't deny that.

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:38.960
 You're not going to get a job if you say, "Well, I don't use AI."

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:40.640
 Well, you better use it.

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:45.000
 I want you to learn how to use it to make you a better programmer, not how to not make

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:46.000
 you a better programmer.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.160
 It's like, "Oh, AI is good enough."

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:52.240
 And any AI technique that I teach or anyone else teaches is going to be out of date so

00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:53.800
 quickly.

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:54.800
 Everything is changing.

00:01:54.800 --> 00:01:56.280
 Every couple of months, things get better.

00:01:56.280 --> 00:02:02.040
 Sometimes I'm using a piece of AI and it's stuck on something and I'll set it aside and

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:05.680
 come back in another month and the models will change and I'll like, "What about that?"

00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:07.720
 And it's like, "Oh, yeah, I'll fix that for you."

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:09.800
 I'm like, "Oh, great."

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:13.520
 But one thing I think is permanent forever, the better you understand programming and the

00:02:13.520 --> 00:02:17.800
 foundations of programming, the better you're going to be at using AI to help you develop

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:19.640
 software.

00:02:19.640 --> 00:02:25.160
 The dangers of AI is that using AI does not mean that you don't need to learn anything

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:28.000
 in a programming class or in a job.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.640
 Believe me, if the only thing you can do is do what AI does for you, then you're probably

00:02:32.640 --> 00:02:35.240
 not going to get a very good job.

00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:39.880
 And if you're taking a class, you become a better programmer, but then you rely on AI

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:44.120
 to actually not study the class material and not learn the class material.

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:48.760
 And then the first part of the course, it's particularly perilous because then you just

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:52.880
 wasted all your time and money, took a course, and now you didn't learn anything.

00:02:52.880 --> 00:02:56.620
 And AI caused you to not learn anything.

00:02:56.620 --> 00:02:58.560
 My thinking on this has evolved over time.

00:02:58.560 --> 00:03:05.580
 So we first heard about AI, like I was in the middle of teaching winter semester 2023.

00:03:05.580 --> 00:03:08.520
 We had a quick faculty meeting.

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:13.440
 We pretty much all, without you coordinating, we just knew that we weren't going to prohibit

00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:15.560
 AI in programming classes.

00:03:15.560 --> 00:03:20.320
 We wanted to find a way to teach with AI, and we wanted to find a way to use AI wisely.

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:26.880
 So for about a year, year and a half, I kind of adjusted my class.

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:32.440
 More paper stuff, et cetera, et cetera, and it had mixed results.

00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:38.640
 The thing I didn't like about it was, and this is true going back over a decade, every

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:43.560
 time I build something that tries to force students to do something my way rather than

00:03:43.560 --> 00:03:50.120
 the easiest way for them, I harm the students who want to learn, and I don't really stop

00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:53.880
 the students who don't want to learn from taking the easy way out.

00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:59.680
 So really, from last semester onward, I'm just treating AI like Stack Overflow.

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:05.960
 I'm not uniquely thinking about it, not doing anything to help it, not doing anything to

00:04:05.960 --> 00:04:07.060
 stop it.

00:04:07.060 --> 00:04:13.440
 As a teacher, you might think it's great to go to college and snap your fingers and get

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:20.340
 A's in all your classes, and in one day, you get a degree and you graduate, and you want

00:04:20.340 --> 00:04:22.760
 to get a great job.

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:27.080
 Unfortunately, when you go to school, you're supposed to learn something.

00:04:27.080 --> 00:04:30.560
 So I'm a teacher, and I'm part of your schooling.

00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:37.120
 So I feel that my job is to take some set of materials, maybe a programming language,

00:04:37.120 --> 00:04:40.840
 and change how you know about it.

00:04:40.840 --> 00:04:44.440
 You don't know something before, and you do know something after, and I got 15 weeks to

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:46.520
 do that.

00:04:46.520 --> 00:04:49.160
 And believe me, I don't want to waste your time.

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:50.240
 I really don't.

00:04:50.240 --> 00:04:56.600
 If I could grab a little USB thing and plug it into the back of your neck like they did

00:04:56.600 --> 00:05:01.480
 in the Matrix and teach you something, I would invent that, and I would do that.

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:07.440
 The human mind just does not accept new knowledge that fast, okay?

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:13.360
 And so we have to come up with a way, and we only have 15 weeks or 10 weeks or whatever.

00:05:13.360 --> 00:05:17.560
 So we have a short period of time and a lot of material to cover.

00:05:17.560 --> 00:05:23.240
 So how do we take a lot of material and cover it in a short period of time?

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:30.360
 And the answer is, you break it into small, doable chunks.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:36.300
 The education word for this is the zone of proximal development, and that is the way

00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:42.140
 you learn is someone like me with an assignment or whatever pushes you outside your comfort

00:05:42.140 --> 00:05:47.680
 zone just a little bit, and then we hang out with you and help you through that, and then

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:48.680
 you learn something.

00:05:48.680 --> 00:05:52.000
 And then a week later, you got a new comfort zone, we push you just a little bit out of

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:53.320
 that comfort zone.

00:05:53.320 --> 00:05:58.620
 So we're keeping you under a little bit of stress each week that hopefully you're adding

00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:00.720
 some stuff up and you're retaining it.

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:04.080
 So some teachers teach too much in a week and then you don't retain it.

00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:09.480
 I try to figure out how much I can teach you in one week that you will retain so your knowledge

00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:11.080
 builds.

00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:16.760
 Naturally, what you find is in the beginning of classes, the amount that I can teach you

00:06:16.760 --> 00:06:20.560
 in a week is smaller than what I can in later, right?

00:06:20.560 --> 00:06:24.440
 Because in the later classes, I can assume that all you'd remember most of the stuff

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:27.940
 that I've already taught you in earlier classes.

00:06:27.940 --> 00:06:31.720
 And this is just natural, it's how you build classes.

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:39.600
 The problem is, is these simple early assignments are much easier for you to complete, so students

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:46.440
 who are tired, who are busy, who just came off of a summer vacation, they're like, "Well,

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:51.000
 I don't really want to work hard this week, I'm going to work twice as hard next week,

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.560
 so I'm going to have AI do the homework this week, yay."

00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:58.100
 So they do that and they're like, "Shoo, I got 100% and AI did it."

00:06:58.100 --> 00:07:01.880
 And then they promise that the second week, they'll work twice as hard and learn everything

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:03.680
 in the first week and everything in the second week.

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:08.480
 And they're like, "Oh wow, I wonder if AI could do this second week homework."

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:11.200
 And then they do have AI do the second week homework.

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:15.560
 And they keep doing this, not because they're bad, students are bad, I mean students are

00:07:15.560 --> 00:07:17.840
 mostly tired.

00:07:17.840 --> 00:07:22.640
 School is hard, especially when you're taking a course that has a schedule and a teacher

00:07:22.640 --> 00:07:26.360
 like me that's telling you what to do every week.

00:07:26.360 --> 00:07:29.960
 When I finally graduated with my PhD, someone asked me, "Do you miss school?"

00:07:29.960 --> 00:07:33.040
 I said, "I don't want any more deadlines, I don't want to be told to do any homework

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:34.040
 on a time."

00:07:34.040 --> 00:07:36.360
 Learning's fun, but having deadlines isn't.

00:07:36.360 --> 00:07:38.560
 Unfortunately, those two things are connected.

00:07:38.560 --> 00:07:43.160
 If you're not forced to do something, you will delay it.

00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:48.520
 So here's the problem, let's just say weeks one through five in this particular course

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:50.640
 are tractable for AI.

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:52.400
 And AI is not really learning anything.

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:56.480
 AI is no smarter at week five than it was at week one.

00:07:56.480 --> 00:08:00.140
 You're not teaching AI anything as you're going through this.

00:08:00.140 --> 00:08:02.360
 If you went through it, you'd be learning something.

00:08:02.360 --> 00:08:07.740
 But AI is already smarter than you and smarter than whatever.

00:08:07.740 --> 00:08:14.560
 So the problem is, is that you get to week six and for whatever reason, AI can't solve

00:08:14.560 --> 00:08:16.020
 your problem.

00:08:16.020 --> 00:08:20.840
 So then what you're forced to do in week six is you're really forced to either drop the

00:08:20.840 --> 00:08:27.180
 class or you have to learn six weeks of material in one week.

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:32.640
 And you've been tired and busy and you've got other classes and it doesn't happen.

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:37.880
 And seven days later, the class is going to take another step, seven more days, class

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:39.440
 is taking another step.

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:42.760
 And this is part of the class where the class is starting to speed up, we call it the knee

00:08:42.760 --> 00:08:44.060
 of the curve.

00:08:44.060 --> 00:08:48.880
 So you picked the exact wrong time to not know what was going on in this class.

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:53.400
 And usually you have to drop the class or get a very low grade in the class because

00:08:53.400 --> 00:09:00.620
 about the one third to one half point is the place in most programming classes where AI

00:09:00.620 --> 00:09:02.960
 just can't do it.

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:05.820
 Before AI, I always made my assessments real work.

00:09:05.820 --> 00:09:09.660
 So writing Django applications is the learning objective of the course.

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:12.680
 Then I want my assignments to be writing Django applications.

00:09:12.680 --> 00:09:16.960
 And so the key thing there is, if I want you to know how to do something and then use AI

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:22.120
 to do it, but you actually learn how to do it and AI makes it better for you, great,

00:09:22.120 --> 00:09:26.320
 I just taught you how to use AI to solve the learning objective of my course, which you

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:28.340
 will then be able to do when you get in your job.

00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:31.520
 So my assignments integrate across many sources.

00:09:31.520 --> 00:09:35.160
 I mentioned I don't give you a little single paragraph that completely describes it and

00:09:35.160 --> 00:09:36.360
 then grade that.

00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:38.320
 No, you got to look at sample code.

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:40.680
 You got to look at some code walkthroughs and demos.

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:42.760
 I'm explaining concepts, right?

00:09:42.760 --> 00:09:45.160
 So then what you got to do is you got to learn the concepts and then you got to pull from

00:09:45.160 --> 00:09:48.480
 places and you got to synthesize all that together.

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:54.400
 And so the problem is, is that AI just wants to look at a few paragraphs and then write

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:56.800
 some code because it can't do that.

00:09:56.800 --> 00:10:03.640
 Like let's write a database application to store and retrieve autos and auto data.

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:06.000
 Well, that's not what my assignments are.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:10.240
 My assignments are look at this code, adapt it, look at that code, adapt it, look at this,

00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:14.300
 read this thing, adapt it, watch this lecture, adapt all that stuff together and synthesize

00:10:14.300 --> 00:10:19.560
 it together and then build a piece of software, not just to solve the problem, but to solve

00:10:19.560 --> 00:10:24.840
 the problem using the techniques that you saw in all the stuff that was in the class.

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:28.960
 Now that doesn't mean that you can't give AI enough context.

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:35.360
 If you were really organized and you figured out every single asset that was in the course

00:10:35.360 --> 00:10:41.720
 this week and you could somehow feed it into AI and build AI's understanding up and said,

00:10:41.720 --> 00:10:48.160
 okay, now using the stuff I just gave you, write an auto tracking, automobile tracking

00:10:48.160 --> 00:10:50.400
 application.

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:51.400
 You might get it.

00:10:51.400 --> 00:10:52.400
 It might.

00:10:52.400 --> 00:10:53.400
 It's not dumb.

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:54.800
 It might.

00:10:54.800 --> 00:11:00.280
 And if you are smart enough to give it enough context to solve one of my assignments, I

00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:02.920
 actually kind of gained some respect for you.

00:11:02.920 --> 00:11:07.060
 And my teaching assistants will sit down in a meeting and tell me, oh yeah, I feed it

00:11:07.060 --> 00:11:08.060
 all into AI.

00:11:08.060 --> 00:11:12.840
 I've got these 14 things in AI and then I tell it to write the code, boof, they probably

00:11:12.840 --> 00:11:14.800
 fed the sample solution in as well.

00:11:14.800 --> 00:11:17.960
 And so yeah, the AI is pretty smart at that point.

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:22.880
 So my auto graders for the software look for specific techniques, not just any old technique,

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:27.280
 but the specific techniques from my course materials in your solution.

00:11:27.280 --> 00:11:31.640
 You can't just take and argue with me and say, you told me to write an automobile database

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:33.480
 and I wrote an automobile database.

00:11:33.480 --> 00:11:35.800
 Too bad it didn't pass the auto grader.

00:11:35.800 --> 00:11:39.680
 Another technique I have is cumulative exams.

00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:44.440
 So like in week one, two, three, and four, in order to discourage you from just using

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:50.440
 AI, I say there'll be a midterm and that midterm will be cumulative.

00:11:50.440 --> 00:11:55.520
 And so if you take weeks one through five plus a little bit and you think you can do

00:11:55.520 --> 00:11:59.380
 that in one week with AI, great, good luck with you.

00:11:59.380 --> 00:12:01.640
 The exams are going to be more difficult.

00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:06.840
 They're going to be potentially as difficult as weeks one through five combined.

00:12:06.840 --> 00:12:09.920
 And if you know everything in week one through five, they're pretty easy.

00:12:09.920 --> 00:12:12.840
 But if you don't, you're not going to do it.

00:12:12.840 --> 00:12:18.600
 And so I generally use about half or a little under half of my scores.

00:12:18.600 --> 00:12:22.640
 Exams are calculated based on exams.

00:12:22.640 --> 00:12:26.400
 And so if you get 100% on the exam assignments and you don't do well on the exams, you kind

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:28.720
 of have a 50% in the class.

00:12:28.720 --> 00:12:34.560
 And so that's another motivation to not just depend on AI because AI won't be able to do

00:12:34.560 --> 00:12:36.560
 the exam for you.

00:12:36.560 --> 00:12:41.880
 And so, I mean, I do let people do some exams online, but sometimes they're just so big

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:45.960
 that AI can't get it right and the auto graders, like I said, are too specific.

00:12:45.960 --> 00:12:48.660
 So here's my recommendations.

00:12:48.660 --> 00:12:52.280
 Don't just rush to the assignments and just smash them out with AI.

00:12:52.280 --> 00:12:55.360
 I understand you're tired and you don't have enough time.

00:12:55.360 --> 00:12:59.920
 The problem is, is that that strategy will initially lead often to success, but that'll

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:03.080
 reinforce your bad choice of not studying, right?

00:13:03.080 --> 00:13:07.600
 If you skim the material before and at least while you're working, and if AI is helping

00:13:07.600 --> 00:13:11.140
 you, maybe some pieces will stick in your mind as you're going through.

00:13:11.140 --> 00:13:13.120
 And don't be so impatient in the first few weeks.

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:16.840
 The first few weeks are the easy part of the class on purpose.

00:13:16.840 --> 00:13:20.800
 So if you don't give yourself a chance to learn in the easy part of the class, you're

00:13:20.800 --> 00:13:22.800
 not going to learn in the hard part of the class.

00:13:22.800 --> 00:13:31.640
 Now, if you already know the material because that's the easy class for you, great.

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:32.760
 You'll be using AI.

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:34.200
 You know how to use AI.

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:35.660
 You could do it in your sleep.

00:13:35.660 --> 00:13:37.120
 So that's not the student I'm talking to.

00:13:37.120 --> 00:13:40.360
 I'm talking about the student that's actually learning this material.

00:13:40.360 --> 00:13:44.100
 And again, the key is a programming course designed to stretch you and teach you a little

00:13:44.100 --> 00:13:49.360
 bit more every week so that when you're done, you can do something big.

00:13:49.360 --> 00:13:53.680
 AI is great and getting better.

00:13:53.680 --> 00:13:58.520
 This is a circuit layout tool that I'm building for a course, an upcoming course I'm going

00:13:58.520 --> 00:14:00.880
 to teach called computer architecture for everybody.

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:04.360
 Hardware, how chips are made.

00:14:04.360 --> 00:14:09.480
 This is based on a piece of software that I learned in grad school like 25 plus years

00:14:09.480 --> 00:14:13.040
 ago called magic, came from my University of California, Berkeley.

00:14:13.040 --> 00:14:18.160
 That's why it's called Mystic because it's like my own version of magic.

00:14:18.160 --> 00:14:19.680
 This does circuit layout.

00:14:19.680 --> 00:14:25.360
 All those layers are polysilicon, n-dope, silicon, p-dope, silicon, metal.

00:14:25.360 --> 00:14:26.360
 You don't need to know this.

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:29.000
 It's not a hardware class.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.640
 And literally, I just talked AI through building all this.

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:35.880
 This is only a couple hundred lines of code.

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:42.600
 And it's a reasonable facsimile of this semi-professional software called magic.

00:14:42.600 --> 00:14:48.520
 And the only part that I really helped in was the circuit simulation because that, you

00:14:48.520 --> 00:14:51.000
 know, maybe the AI will figure that out too eventually.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:56.120
 But I used some recursion and some other tricks to make the little pluses and minuses go.

00:14:56.120 --> 00:15:01.160
 But I've been doing these kinds of small tasks with AI for a while.

00:15:01.160 --> 00:15:05.920
 And I'll just say I'm really starting to believe.

00:15:05.920 --> 00:15:12.040
 I'm starting to believe that AI is more of a partner than like barely capable of doing

00:15:12.040 --> 00:15:13.960
 the simplest things.

00:15:13.960 --> 00:15:19.600
 And as I increasingly trust and believe in AI as my partner, I'm starting to communicate

00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:22.560
 with it as if it's more intelligent.

00:15:22.560 --> 00:15:29.560
 So my conversations with AI are longer, more jargon loaded, as if I was talking to someone

00:15:29.560 --> 00:15:31.980
 who is almost as good as me.

00:15:31.980 --> 00:15:38.440
 And so, and I will say that as I increase the sophistication with which I communicate

00:15:38.440 --> 00:15:41.680
 with AI, I am getting better results from AI.

00:15:41.680 --> 00:15:46.760
 And so this goes back to, if you're good at programming and you're good at understanding

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:52.160
 problems, then your communication with AI can be at a much higher level with much more

00:15:52.160 --> 00:15:55.680
 detail and you'll get better results.

